{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.08,0.21,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44559"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29444"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"94"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"6630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11531"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44559"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man complains of left calf pain after walking 300 metres, which is relieved by rest. His medical history includes hypertension and he has a 40-pack-year smoking history. He takes atenolol. On examination his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg and pulse 84/min. His right femoral and distal pulses are all palpable and of good volume. The left popliteal pulse is reduced in volume and the distal pulses are not palpable. The ankle-brachial index is 0.8 on the right and 0.5 on the left (normal 0.9 -1.3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from counselling on smoking cessation, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duplex ultrasonography","Angiography","CT angiography","MR angiography","Plethysmography"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe normal range for the ankle-brachial index is between 0.9 and 1.3. A value under 0.9 indicates a degree of impairment of the circulation to the legs and feet. Values between 0.4 - 0.9 indicate the presence of mild to moderate peripheral arterial disease and a value of less than 0.4 is indicative of severe disease. A patient with severe disease will require definitive imaging (\u003Cstrong\u003Eangiography\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E) as a prelude to some form of surgical intervention. This particular patient does not require such an active approach at this stage, and his problem can be approached by starting with \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E to identify the site of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with intermittent claudication and an ABI between 0.4 - 0.9 will require some form of imaging to define the site and severity of the obstruction."],"references":["Kullo IJ, Rooke TW. Peripheral Artery Disease. N Engl J Med 2016; 374:861-71."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29444"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29444"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-23T10:04:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-23T10:04:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44559"}}},"meta":{"can